<!-- MODALS -->
<div class="modal-overlay" id="modal-post1">
  <div class="modal">
    <button class="modal-close" onclick="closeModal('post1')">✕</button>
    <div class="modal-tag">Entrepreneurship</div>
    <div class="modal-title">Building FourMeasure: What Nobody Tells You About Starting a Company</div>
    <div class="modal-body">
      <p>When I decided to build FourMeasure, I wasn't following a playbook. There was no roadmap, no investor writing checks, and no guarantee that any of it would work. What I had was a conviction that music deserved the same kind of thoughtful, social discovery layer that film found in platforms like Rotten Tomatoes or IMDB and a willingness to do whatever it took to make it real.</p>
      <p>The first thing nobody tells you is how long the early phase actually takes. Before a single line of code was written, I spent weeks just talking to people. Asking them how they discover music, what frustrates them, what they wish existed. Those conversations were humbling. Half the time people would describe something completely different from what I had imagined. But that's the process. The idea on paper is never the real idea. The real idea only emerges once you've pressure-tested it against actual human beings.</p>
      <p>Building the team came next, and that was its own education. Recruiting a technical co-founder when you're a marketing student with no external funding is a trust exercise more than anything else. I had to sell the vision hard not just the product, but the market, the timing, and most importantly, why I was the right person to build it. Preparing the CTO pitch deck, drafting equity agreements, thinking through vesting schedules none of that is covered in a business school curriculum. You learn it by doing it, by making mistakes, and by iterating fast.</p>
      <p>What I know now that I didn't know when I started: the hardest part of building a company isn't the product. It's staying in motion when nothing is certain. It's making a decision with 60% of the information you wish you had, then committing to it completely. FourMeasure has made me more decisive, more resilient, and more honest with myself than anything else in my life. And we're just getting started.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="modal-overlay" id="modal-post2">
  <div class="modal">
    <button class="modal-close" onclick="closeModal('post2')">✕</button>
    <div class="modal-tag">Cinema &amp; Music</div>
    <div class="modal-title">Why the Arts Are the Most Underrated Business Education</div>
    <div class="modal-body">
      <p>Business school teaches you frameworks. The arts teach you how people actually feel. And in a world where every product is a commodity and every brand is fighting for attention, the second skill is worth infinitely more.</p>
      <p>I grew up loving cinema. Not just watching films, but studying them the way a director builds tension through pacing, the way a score tells you how to feel before the dialogue does, the way a single image can carry more meaning than ten minutes of exposition. What I didn't realize until I started building FourMeasure is how directly those instincts translate to product and brand thinking.</p>
      <p>Great cinema is built around empathy. A director has to understand what an audience wants to feel, then construct an experience that delivers it often without the audience even realizing it's happening. That is, word for word, what good marketing does. When I'm thinking about how to position FourMeasure, I'm not thinking about feature lists or competitive analysis. I'm thinking about the moment a user opens the app, what they're feeling, what they want, and what story I can tell them that makes them feel seen.</p>
      <p>Music operates on the same logic but at an even more primal level. Music bypasses cognition entirely and lands straight in the body. That's why it's such a powerful branding tool and why I became obsessed with building a platform that takes it seriously. FourMeasure wants to treat music like culture, not a commodity. That distinction came directly from years of engaging with music not as a product, but as an art form.</p>
      <p>My advice to any business student reading this: go watch Kurosawa. Go listen to a full album front to back with no distractions. Go see live music and pay attention to how the crowd moves. The patterns you'll find there tension, release, narrative, community are the same patterns that drive every business that has ever mattered. The arts aren't a break from business thinking. They are business thinking, at its deepest level.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="modal-overlay" id="modal-post3">
  <div class="modal">
    <button class="modal-close" onclick="closeModal('post3')">✕</button>
    <div class="modal-tag">Personal Growth</div>
    <div class="modal-title">My Entrepreneurship Journey at the University of Miami</div>
    <div class="modal-body">
      <p>I didn't arrive at the University of Miami as a founder. I arrived as someone who knew they wanted to build something, but had no idea what that actually meant in practice. The years since have been the most accelerated education of my life and most of it happened outside the classroom.</p>
      <p>Before UM, I was at Miami Dade College. I finished with a 4.0, made the Dean's List, and got into Pi Kappa Phi Honors Society. People sometimes underestimate community college as a stepping stone, but it was the right environment for me at the time lower stakes, high focus, and proof to myself that I could execute at a high level when I committed fully. That mentality carried directly into everything I've done since.</p>
      <p>At UM's Herbert Business School, I was awarded a Presidential Scholarship and made the Provost's Honor Roll. But the most important things I learned weren't in those courses. They came from building FourMeasure in parallel from the tension of trying to perform academically while simultaneously running a company, managing equity negotiations, recruiting engineers, and designing marketing campaigns. That tension forced me to develop systems, prioritize ruthlessly, and make decisions fast.</p>
      <p>The Entrepreneurship minor was a genuine complement to those real-world experiences. Professors who brought in founders, case studies of companies that failed and why, frameworks for thinking about market sizing and competitive positioning all of it became more useful because I had live context to apply it to. Theory and practice in direct conversation with each other is the most effective form of learning I've found.</p>
      <p>The most important lesson UM has taught me isn't in any syllabus. It's this: the people around you set your ceiling. Surrounding yourself with ambitious, intelligent, hungry people raises what you believe is possible for yourself. Miami itself is a city that doesn't apologize for ambition. It's international, it's fast, it's competitive in the best way. I wouldn't have wanted to learn to build a company anywhere else.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

